definition.value: A metabolite of aflatoxin B1
A member of the class of aflatoxins that is aflatoxin B1 in which the hydrogen at the pro-3S position is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A metabolite of aflatoxin B1
A metabolite of aflatoxin B1
A metabolite of aflatoxin B1
A member of the class of aflatoxins that is obtained by the formal epoxidation across the 8,9-double bond of aflatoxin B1.
A metabolite of aflatoxin B1

An organic anion that is the conjugate base of 6-linalyl-2-O,3-dimethylflaviolin, obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of 2-O,3-dimethylflaviolin, obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A hydrochloride obtained by reaction of oxycodone with one molar equivalent of hydrochloric acid.  It is a moderately potent opioid analgesic, generally used for relief of moderate to severe pain.
A hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 3-methylflaviolin in which the hydroxyl hydrogens at positions 2 and 7 are replaced by methyl and geranyl groups respectively.

A polyketide and carboxamide produced by a (Pseudomonas) bacterial endosymbiont of certain rove beetles (genus Paederus). Pederin is the agent responsible for the vesicant effects (linear or Paederus dermatitis) when the beetle is crushed against the skin. It is a powerful inhibitor of protein biosynthesis and mitosis and a potent antitumour agent.
Any compound that causes severe skin, eye and mucosal pain and irritation.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate function of dolichyl diphosphate group. It is the major structure at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A 3-oxo-5alpha- steroid that is 5alpha-pregane-3-one carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at the 20beta-position.
A C21-steroid that is cortisol in which the 21-hydroxy group has been oxidised to the corresponding aldehyde.
A C21-steroid that is cortisone in which the 21-hydroxy group has been oxidised to the corresponding aldehyde.
An alpha-amino-acid cation residue obtained by protonation of the amino function of any N-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino-acid residue obtained by formal N-acetylation of any N-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue.
A zwitterionic group obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any (gamma-L-glutamyl) N-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An 11-oxo steroid that is corticosterone in which the hydroxy substituent at the 11beta position has been oxidised to give the corresponding ketone.
A C21-steroid that is progesterone carrying two additional oxo substituents at positions 11 and 21
A steroid acid anion that is the conjugate base of isoursodeoxycholic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3beta-hydroxy-7-oxo-5beta-cholan-24-oic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A bile acid anion that is the conjugate base of ursodeoxycholic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A bile acid anion that is the conjugate base of 7-oxolithocholic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any inducer of heat shock protein 70.
An anionic ganglioside that is the conjugate base of fucosyl GM1 arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any alpha-amino acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A single-strand DNA oligonucleotide comprised of four deoxyadenosine, eight deoxycytidine, four thymidine and two deoxyguanidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence C-C-G-T-C-C-A-T-A-A-T-C-A-C-T-C-G-C.

A single-strand DNA oligonucleotide comprised of three deoxyadenosine, two deoxycytidine, four thymidine and eight deoxyguanidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence G-C-G-T-G-A-T-T-A-T-G-G-A-C, with a (6-4) lesion at the central two thymidine residues.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-hydroxybutanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the terminal carboxy group of C-terminal L-Cys-L-Leu-L-Val-L-Cys residue.
An organoheteryl group derived from L-Ala-L-Leu-L-valinamide-N-CH=CH-S.
A linear trisaccharide consisting of three L-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptose residues joined sequentially by (1->7) and (1->3) linkages.

Any organooxygen compound that is a polyhydroxy-aldehyde or -ketone, or a compound derived from one. Carbohydrates contain only carbon, hydrogen and oxygen and usually have an empirical formula Cm(H2O)n; carbohydrate derivatives may contain other elements by substitution or condensation.

A linear trisaccharide comprising two L-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptose residues and a 3-deoxy-alpha-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonic acid (2-keto-3-deoxy-alpha-D-mannooctanoic acid, alpha-Kdo) residue in a (1->3), (1->5) sequence.

A linear tetrasaccharide comprising three L-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptose residues and a 3-deoxy-alpha-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonic acid (2-keto-3-deoxy-alpha-D-mannooctanoic acid, alpha-Kdo) residue in a (1->7), (1->3), (1->5) sequence.
The inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of iron(III) oxide-hydroxide; major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of phenols that is 2,4-dimethylphenol which is substituted at positions 3 and 6 by 4,5-dihydro-1H-imidazol-2-ylmethyl and tert-butyl groups, respectively. A direct-acting sympathomimetic with marked alpha-adrenergic activity, it is a vasoconstrictor that is used (generally as the hydrochloride salt) to relieve nasal congestion.
A naphthoate that is the conjugate base of 3-methoxy-5-methyl-1-naphthoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of p-[(trifluoromethyl)sulfanyl]benzoic acid with the amino group of (2S)-2-amino-3-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile in which the hydroxy group has been converted to the corresponding 5-cyano-2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl ether. A broad-spectrum nematicide, it is used to control gastrointestinal roundworms in sheep and goats.
An EC 2.7.11.* (protein-serine/threonine kinase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any [hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase (NADPH)] kinase (EC 2.7.11.31).
An antagonist at the bone morphogenetic protein receptor.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of clavaldehyde, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of 2-hydroxyhepta-2,4-dienedioic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of 2-oxohept-4-ene-1,7-dioic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that results from the removal of all five protons from the phosphate and carboxylic acid groups of 2-hydroxyglutaryl-CoA. Major structure at pH 7.3 (Marvin 6.2.0)
Conjugated acid of chebi:78395 This is an attempt to handle the fact that the free amino group should be charged but not the amido groups
